Rating: 4
I've made this bread three times now and it's come out perfect every time. I made just a few modifications. As suggested, I added more salt -- 2 1/2 tsp. Also, I followed the method used for the Yankee Oatmeal Molasses Bread on Epicurious (which is also great), soaking the oatmeal in 1 3/4 cups boiling water (along with the butter and most of the sugar). I used the remaining 3/4 cup water to proof the yeast with 1 tbsp. of the brown sugar, then after 10 mins. added it to the oatmeal mixture. I let my Kitchenaid do most of the hard work mixing the whole thing (until it starts bumping up and down!), then have fun kneading it on a board for a while. I also did two rises. With regular bread being so expensive lately, not to mention artisan breads, it's been fun to return to bread-baking over the past few months. You get healthier, tastier bread for a whole lot less money.

Rating: 4
Great recipe. I used half the yeast, let it rise for an hour each time (what's the rush?) and also used part milk for the liquid and added the wheat germ as someone else suggested. Also, added used almost 2 tsp. of salt (as others suggested.) A slow rise is always better. Turned out really great.

Rating: 2
I've made this bread three times now. The first time was exactly as written. Wow. Not enough salt, too wet, too much yeast and not enough kneading time. My other attempts yielded much better results. I added one tablespoon of salt, used half bread flour, half all-purpose (adding all six cups of flour before mixing and kneading, half the yeast and kneaded for about one half hour. Also, I glazed the tops with an egg beaten with a tablespoon of cream. Very nice.

Rating: 4
this bread is amazing... so far i've made it three times (but i half the recipe each time so i get just one loaf when i bake it up), and each time i changed something slightly. so far, my favorite variation is to add a half-cup of wheat germ in place of one half cup of flour. it gives the bread a really nice nutty flavor on top of the oats, and adds some additional nutritional merit as well. just be sure to add salt (i do about 1 to 2 tsp), or the bread is a bit flavorless.

